    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-07-17T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-07-17T06:00:00-05:00" n="64"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d64">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">741.60D/14: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Finland</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Schoenfeld</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Helsinki</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-07-17T13:00:00+02:00"
                            >July 17, 1941—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 3:50 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>298. Having in mind Finnish Foreign Minister’s statement to me yesterday as
                    reported in my 292 that no conclusions were being drawn by Finnish Government
                    from new situation brought about by British-Soviet Alliance, I asked British
                    Minister this morning whether British Government intends to withdraw him. He
                    told me that matter is left largely to his discretion and that balance of
                    advantage seems to be for the present in remaining here for reasons including
                    the following: that British Government which is anxious to secure use of
                    substantial Finnish shipping may be better able to obtain it by negotiation than
                    by seizure at sea; that as the fighting front against Russians moves eastward,
                    Finland’s position should improve and German influence lessen to benefit of
                    Finnish independence; that there seems to be no disposition in Finland to force
                    the issue and hasten break with Britain; and that presence of Finnish Minister
                    at London doubtless facilitates reports to Finnish Government which serves to
                    counteract German influence here. Furthermore, British Government feels that
                    Vereker and his staff can be more useful by remaining insofar as supply of
                    information is concerned. For the time being, therefore, I gather British
                    Government will not break with Finland and British Legation will not be
                    withdrawn.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Schoenfeld</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
